04461nam a22006735i 9780674269385DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742693857 a10.4159/97806742693852doi  a(DE-B1597)590547  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBP189.4b.Z53 2021eb 7aREL0900002bisacsh04a297.6/109582231 aZiad, Waleed, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHidden Caliphate :bSufi Saints beyond the Oxus and Indus /cWaleed Ziad. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSufis created the most extensive Muslim revivalist network in Asia before the twentieth century, generating a vibrant Persianate literary, intellectual, and spiritual culture while tying together a politically fractured world. In a pathbreaking work combining social history, religious studies, and anthropology, Waleed Ziad examines the development across Asia of Muslim revivalist networks from the eighteenth to the twentieth centuries. At the center of the story are the Naqshbandi-Mujaddidi Sufis, who inspired major reformist movements and articulated effective social responses to the fracturing of Muslim political power amid European colonialism. In a time of political upheaval, the Mujaddidis fused Persian, Arabic, Turkic, and Indic literary traditions, mystical virtuosity, popular religious practices, and urban scholasticism in a unified yet flexible expression of Islam. The Mujaddidi “Hidden Caliphate,” as it was known, brought cohesion to diverse Muslim communities from Delhi through Peshawar to the steppes of Central Asia. And the legacy of Mujaddidi Sufis continues to shape the Muslim world, as their institutional structures, pedagogies, and critiques have worked their way into leading social movements from Turkey to Indonesia, and among the Muslims of China. By shifting attention away from court politics, colonial actors, and the standard narrative of the “Great Game,” Ziad offers a new vision of Islamic sovereignty. At the same time, he demonstrates the pivotal place of the Afghan Empire in sustaining this vast inter-Asian web of scholastic and economic exchange. Based on extensive fieldwork across Afghanistan, Uzbekistan, and Pakistan at madrasas, Sufi monasteries, private libraries, and archives, Hidden Caliphate reveals the long-term influence of Mujaddidi reform and revival in the eastern Muslim world, bringing together seemingly disparate social, political, and intellectual currents from the Indian Ocean to Siberia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aCaliphatexHistory. 0aDaʿwah (Islam)xHistory. 0aIslam and politicsxHistory. 0aMuslim saintszAsia, CentralvBiography. 0aMuslim saintszAsia, CentralxHistory. 0aMuslim saintszPakistanvBiography. 0aMuslim saintszPakistanxHistory. 0aSufismxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Sufi.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073911440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674269385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674269385/original  a978-3-11-073911-4  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK